summary.seg: This manuscript contains Excerpts from Greek historical texts and notes, written by an English scholar at the end of the 17th century.

The codex contains writing at the front and the rear, with a large number of blank leaves in the middle. The scribe rotated the volume in order to write the texts at the rear of the manuscript, and started to write from the back, as if it was the front: therefore, in the last part of the manuscript, the text appears upside down and the order is backwards.

At one end of the codex the scribe copied notes and transcriptions in English and Latin, from Cuspinianus' commentary on Cassiodorus' Consules Romani (1553) and Henschenius' apparatus to the Pontifical Chronology (1685), and a series of excerpts, in Greek, from Flavius Josephus' Antiquitates Iudaicae and Herodotus' Historiae. The excerpts are arranged in chronological order, from the time of Seth, the third son of Adam and Eve, to the pharaoh Chephren (ca. 2575-2465 BCE).

At the other end, the same scribe copied excerpts from two Byzantine chronicles, the Chronicon Paschale ('Easter or Paschal Chronicle'), and George Synkellos' Ekloge chronographias ( Ecloga chronographica, 'Selection from Chronographers'); the extracts were copied from two printed editions, of 1688 and 1652 respectively. The year 1688 is therefore a terminus ante quem non for the production of the manuscript (i.e. the date before which it cannot have been copied). The manuscript was possibly copied before 1701, since this date is cited in a note on the left pastedown, which seems to be related to the acquisition of the volume. This time span is confirmed by the watermarks found in the manuscript.

The material collected in the manuscript suggests that the scribe, probably an English scholar, was possibly preparing a work on ancient chronology (see M.R. James, A Descriptive Catalogue of the Manuscripts in the Library of Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge (Cambridge, 1895), p. 125).

msItem.title: Notes and transcriptions from Cuspinianus' commentary on Cassiodorus' Consules Romani and Henschenius' apparatus to the Pontifical Chronology
msItem.note:
Notes and trascriptions from:
Cuspinianus' commentary on Cassiodorus' Consules Romani: Ioannis Cuspiniani, viri clarissimi, divi quondam Maximiliani imperatoris a Consilijs, et oratoris : de consulibus Romanorum commentarii, ex optimis vetustissimisque authoribus collecti. Praefertur his commentariis, Sexti Ruffi V. Consularis rerum gestarum Pop. Rom. deque accessione imperii epitome, cum eiusdem Cuspiniani eruditissimis scholiis. Magni Aurelii Cassiodori Senatoris Chronicon, sive de consulibus Romanorum libellus, passim Cuspiniani commentariis insertus. Nicolai Gerbelii in eosdem commentarios, ad ornatiss, uirum D. Ioannem Iacobum Fuggerum praefatio: in qua de chronographis, apparatus de eorum discordia, deque huius operis maxima utilitate. Ad haec rerum atque verborum toto opere memorabilium index locupletissimus, Basileae 1553
Henschenius' apparatus to the Pontifical Chronology: Danielis Papebrochii Conatus chronico-historicus ad catalogum Romanorum Pontificum, Cum praevio ad eumdem Apparatu Godefridi Henschenii atque Petri Possini a Sancto Petro usque ad Innocentium undecimum, Antuerpiae 1685

msItem.title: Excerpts from Flavius Josephus' Antiquitates Iudaicae and Herodotus' Historiae
msItem.incipit: f. 6r A Periodi Iulianae seculo IX ad XXIII inclusive. Seth. Ex Ioseph. Antiquit., L. I c. 3. Γίνονται μὲν οὖν παῖδες αὐτoῦ ἄλλοι τὲ πλείους καὶ Σῆθος
msItem.explicit: f. 37v ταῦτα ἕξ τε καὶ ἑκατὸν λογίζονται ἔτεα ... κατὰ ταῦτα τὰ χωρία
msItem.note: The excerpts are organized chronologically (from A Periodi Iulianae seculo IX ad XXIII inclusive to Periodi Iulianae seculum XXXIX) and thematically (for example, f. 6r Seth, f. 8r De Aegyptiorum diis, semideis et cultibus religiosis, f. 12r Confusio linguarum, f. 32v David Rex

Last excerpt: Herodotus, Historiae ( N.G. Wilson, Herodoti Historiae (Oxford, 2015), vol. 1, book 1, section 128; TLG 0016.002)

msItem.note: The excerpts are copied from the 1688 edition by Du Fresne ( Πασχάλιον seu Chronicon Paschale a mundo condito ad Heraclii imperatoris annum vicesimum [...], cura et studio Caroli Du Fresne, D. support.material: Western paper, folded in folio. Watermarks: ff. 1-274 Lily on a cartouche, under the cartouche 4WR, with countermark WK ( 150 72 ), in the centre of the folio, similar to Heawood Lily 1785, 1785a, which are dated in 1670.

foliation.p: Modern foliation (2020) in pencil (the images have been taken before the codex was foliated, therefore the numbers are not present in the digitisation): i + 1-274 + ii

Each leaf has been divided into two columns; the scribe numbered the columns 1-200; the first 7 columns coincide with a page, in the following leaves there are two columns per page; the succession of the numbers, after column 10, restarts from 7 coll. 1-11, 7[a]-11[a], 12-200.

collation.p: The quires have been sewn very tightly, there is no numbering of the quires, therefore it is not possible to ascertain with certainty the original collation.

supportDesc.condition: The manuscript is in good condition.

layoutDesc.layout: Irregular layout. 2-3 colums, mostly 2 columns of 56-75 lines. ca. 255 ca. 400

handNote.p: ff. 1r-37v, 251v-272v Hand A: a western European hand datable in the late 17th c., vertical.
The text is written in brown ink

additions.p: On the left pastedown, in the upper left corner, a note is written in brown ink, indicating the price of the manuscript and the date of September 1701: Pret. 10 s. Septemb. 1701. In the centre, the present shelfmark, gr. 105, is written in pencil.
On f. 274v is written, in pencil, the former shelfmark, Δ.5.20.

binding.p: Modern western reversed skin binding, couched-laminate boards. Blind tooling on both covers: a blind tooled rectangular frame filled with a vegetal decoration. Blind tooling on the cover's edges. 425 280 68

origin.p: The manuscript was copied by an English scholar in the late 17th century (after 1688) (see Summary), in England. This dating is supported also by the watermark of the paper.

history.acquisition: The codex was possibly acquired in 1701, as this date appears with the indication of the price of 10 shillings on the left pastedown.

recordHist.source: Description (2020) draws partly on M. R. James, A Descriptive Catalogue of the Manuscripts in the Library of Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1895), p. 125.
